<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by Martin Matthews, National Leader of Governance</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">AFS0009</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Martin Matthews, National Leader of Governance</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This is my personal submission of evidence to the Education Committee </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">inquiry into certain aspects of the academies programme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. The opinions expressed here are my own and do not reflect those of the DfE </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">through</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> my designation as a National Leader of Governance.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Overview</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">I have served on a number of different governing bodies as governor, vice chair and chair. Cumulatively I have over 35 years’ experience</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as a governor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and I have lead several schools through significant changes. I have been a teacher, parent, LA, foundation and community governor at different times.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> I have been a governor in a number of different LA’s.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">I was designated as a National Leader of Governance by the National College</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for teaching and Leadership</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in April 2012 having served as a Greater Manchester Governor Champion </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2009-11</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. In the next few years I will have served more years as a governor (cumulatively) than I have been alive. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Executive Summary</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There are consistent and continuing concerns expressed in many schools regarding issues in the academy programme, particularly academy chains. Governors remain unconvinced of the value of academisation to many primary schools. Governors are the decision makers in this situation unless it is a forced conversion due to underperformance. The heart of the concern is what benefit the child in the classroom would gain from their school becoming an academy. </span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The effectiveness of academisation in narrowing the gap for disadvantaged children, and what further steps should be taken within the academies system to bring about a transformational impact on student outcomes;</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">I have no comment on this aspect.</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The process for approving, compelling and establishing academies and free schools, including working with sponsors;</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The position where a school is being compelled to become an academy should never be reached. The Local Authority (LA) should be clear well in advance of what measures are required to prevent children’s education deteriorating to this point. The deterioration will have been observed year on year and LA’s should be taking prompt action. There is a significant reluctance in some LA’s to impose Interim Executive Boards (IEB</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">) to replace failing governing bodies. This issue should be tackled quickly and LA’s encouraged to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">use their powers sooner. This should be part of an overall graduated response. If LA’s are seen to be not using these powers the DfE should remove them.</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The role of the Secretary of State in intervening in and supporting failing academies, and how this role will work as the programme expands; </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There are academy chains rapidly becoming “too big to fail”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> this position is avoidable.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> A </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">maximum number of students/schools per academy chain</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> should be set</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Larger chains should be broken up.</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The functions and responsibilities in relation to academies and free schools of local authorities and other organisations operating between the Secretary of State and individual schools; what these functions and responsibilities should be; and what gaps there are in support for schools at this level;</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">LA’s should imaginatively execute their monitoring functions. Monitoring functions should equally apply to all categories of school. Reporting to the DfE should be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> standardised,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> transparent and prompt.</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What role academy chains play or should play in the new school landscape; how accountable they are; and what issues they raise with regard to governance arrangements;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The role of academy chains in the education landscape will continue to develop. There are a number of factors </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">which give cause for concern.</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Chains are being allowed to grow to a size where they are becoming </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">too big to fail</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. This is a serious concern. The DfE has not had to cope with a large chain which has systemically failed. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> maximum size of chain should be set.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Disaster recovery plans for how to react to a chain which fails should be dra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">wn up by the DfE. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The chain board has no accountability to local stakeholders.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is no representation mechanism for local schools on the chain board. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is no mechanism for schools within the chain to remove directors/board members.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">New academy chain board members are selected and appointed by existing board members. This system is too insular and has the potential to go seriously wrong with significant amounts of tax payers money.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The chain board can allocate expenses or remuneration to its members and has no accountability </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">or transparency </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">measure for this.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is no mechanism for competitive appointment of board members based on skills and experience.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is no requirement to have a person with substantial governance expertise on the chain board. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Chains mirror many of the functions of LA’s but cannot be inspected by Ofsted. They should be subject to the same inspections as LA’s and the same sanctions.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The lack of accountability and transparency is a concern.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he executive functions of the school governing body wholly transfer to the chain and cannot be withdrawn</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> once the school joins the chain</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. The chain has carte blanche to deleg</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ate which functions it sees fit. Residual legal functions should exist including the ability to withdraw from the chain or move to another chain. Standards of expected delegation should be documented by the DfE as they are for maintained schools.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> school cannot leave</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a chain and there should be a mechanism for schools to leave or move to another chain.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">When a chain covers more than one LA area there is no funding formula to decide what capitation per anum the school should receive. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is no maximum limit set to the amount of top slice a chain can apply to a school budget.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Academy chains can deploy any staff member to any site within the chain as they are the employer. Employees dislike this uncertainty and it affects recruitment and retention. </span></li></ul><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The appropriateness of academy status for primary schools and what special factors apply;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> and what evidence there is that academy status can bring value for money either for individual primary schools or for the system as a whole;</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Academy status remains an unconvincing option for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">circa </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">16,000 of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">circa </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">17,000 primary schools in England. Special factors which apply to primary schools are numerous. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Factors include:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The business model for primary schools is different to secondary schools. I think this contributes significantly to the small number of primary schools which have</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> voluntarily</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> become academies.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The number of support staff; most primary schools have minimal numbers of support staff. Schools buy in functions from third party suppliers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. M</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">any continue to receive bundled services from their LA as part of the LA top slice of funding. Unbundling these functions require top quality, well trained and more numerous staff which most primary schools do not have. These functions are often done by the head teacher and academisation would add considerably to their non education workload, shifting the emphasis of their role from children and parents</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to administration</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The training of support staff; the number of schools business managers trained to degree standard is tiny. Manchester Metropolitan University graduates less than 10 people per anum in school business management.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The base line skill set of support staff; many support staff have been in post for considerable time and their role has evolved around them. The baseline skillset is now complex and industry sector specific. On the job training is frequently the only way to obtain the necessary skillset.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The average maintained primary school is a size between two economic units common in the independent sector. Economics would pressure the school to shrink or grow if it converted to an academy. This factor is little understood by schools considering conversion and it would decrease value for money. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The local footfall of stakeholders</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> at primary schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is considerable in comparison to secondary schools. They are represented on the governing body. Breakin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">g the local link is unappealing to the governing body.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The replacement of a governing body with a local governing body is unappealing to many schools. The LGB itself has no legal function</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, cannot hold the chain to account and any appointees can be dismissed without any form of recourse.</span></li></ul><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What alternatives to sponsored academy status should be offered to failing primary schools.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Alternatives to academisation are rarely explored. The variety of options is much wider than academy or maintained school. Options include:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">School closure; there is still a reluctance to close poorly performing schools. If this is a viable option it may be th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e quickest, most cost effective,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> simplest</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and best</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> option for students and their families. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">School amalgamation; this option is rarely used. Rather than being moved into the academy sector there is the option for a poorly performing school to be taken over by a better performing school. This could provide a graduated response</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to poor performance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and could be significantly better value for money than academisation.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Federation; this was the vogue some years a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">go and is still legal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. This would enable schools close to being good to be supported by another school and then choose to remain or become a single unit again. This would add a graduated response and be significantly more cost effective than </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">academisation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>